  "market_context": "ETH trading lower on the hourly chart after respecting the lower half of the prior daily candle's wick. A bearish fair value gap is identified above current price as a potential point of interest for a short continuation, with the daily open below acting as a downside reference.",
  "key_observation": "The fair value gap printed without a wick, leaving the entry shy of the zone. Price then returned on the higher time frame candle specifically to form the wick into the FVG before producing an aggressive bearish closure and continuing lower toward the daily open.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the bearish fair value gap above price as a valid point of interest after invalidating other levels.",
    "Step 2: Let price trade lower first, noting this usually means at minimum a return to the daily opening price.",
    "Step 3: Observed price leaving shy of the fair value gap on the 1H, meaning the entry could be missed if only watching the LTF.",
    "Step 4: Replayed the higher time frame candle and showed the FVG initially printed without a wick, then price returned specifically to put in that wick on the HTF.",
    "Step 5: Confirmed the aggressive bearish closure after the wick formed, validating the FVG reaction.",
    "Step 6: Tracked continuation lower with each day respecting the lower half of the prior day's wick/candle.",
    "Step 7: Noted that after three days of expansion into lows, he avoids price as a new phase of delivery (consolidation, retracement, or reversal) becomes likely."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price respected the fair value gap on the higher time frame wick, produced an aggressive bearish closure, and continued lower toward the daily open and beyond; no specific R outcome stated.",
  "lessons": "A fair value gap may print without a wick on the lower time frame, causing a missed entry. Watching the higher time frame candle reveals when price returns to form that wick into the FVG, offering the actual reaction point before continuation.",
